---
import BaseLayout from '../components/layout/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About — Propaedia" description="About this web edition of the Propaedia Outline of Knowledge">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold text-gray-900 mb-8">About This Project</h1>

    <div class="prose-propaedia">
      <h2>The Propaedia</h2>
      <p>
        The <em>Propaedia</em>, or "Outline of Knowledge," is one of three parts of the
        <em>Encyclopaedia Britannica</em> (15th edition). Created under the direction of
        Mortimer J. Adler, it provides a systematic classification of all human knowledge
        organized into <strong>10 Parts</strong>, <strong>41 Divisions</strong>, and
        <strong>177 Sections</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Unlike a traditional encyclopedia arranged alphabetically, the Propaedia presents
        knowledge hierarchically — showing how subjects relate to one another within the
        broader landscape of human understanding.
      </p>

      <h2>This Web Edition</h2>
      <p>
        This site presents the Propaedia's knowledge hierarchy in
        a navigable web format. Each of the 177 sections includes:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>The original hierarchical subject outline</li>
        <li>Cross-references to related sections</li>
        <li>Historical Macropaedia article recommendations</li>
        <li>Curated <strong>Oxford Very Short Introduction</strong> (VSI) book recommendations for modern readers</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Oxford Very Short Introductions</h2>
      <p>
        This web edition adds carefully matched titles from Oxford University Press's
        <em>Very Short Introductions</em> series as a supplementary reading layer for
        modern readers. They sit alongside the historical Macropaedia reading lists;
        they are not intended to replace Britannica's own longer articles.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each recommendation includes a short rationale explaining how the VSI maps to
        the section's subject matter. Recommendations are sorted by relevance using
        keyword data sourced from Oxford Academic.
      </p>

      <details class="mt-2 rounded-lg border border-gray-200 bg-gray-50 px-4 py-3">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-sm font-semibold text-gray-700">How relevance is calculated</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-3 text-sm text-gray-600">
          <p>
            Each book receives a relevance score based on how closely it relates to
            the section you are viewing. A book whose <strong>title</strong> directly
            names the topic scores highest — if the section is about economics, a book
            called <em>Economics</em> will naturally rank above a more specialised title
            like <em>Behavioural Economics</em>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Beyond the title, the scoring considers the book's <strong>subject
            keywords</strong> (sourced from Oxford Academic) and how well its
            <strong>description</strong> aligns with the topics covered in the
            section's outline.
          </p>
          <p>
            When you click an outline item to filter the list, the scoring also looks
            at the <strong>sub-topics</strong> beneath that item. A book that touches
            many of those sub-topics ranks higher than one that strongly matches just
            one narrow area. This favours comprehensive introductions over highly
            specialised treatments when you are browsing at a broader level of the
            outline.
          </p>
          <p>
            The relevance percentage shown on each card is relative — the best-scoring
            book in the current view is always shown as 100%, and the others are scaled
            proportionally.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <p>
        The VSI catalogue and keyword data were last updated in <strong>March 2025</strong>,
        covering 793 titles from the Oxford Very Short Introductions series.
      </p>

      <h2>Technical Details</h2>
      <p>
        This site is built with <a href="https://astro.build">Astro</a>, uses static
        site generation for fast loading, and is hosted on GitHub Pages. Search is
        powered by <a href="https://pagefind.app">Pagefind</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
